Collections.binarySearch(list, 40) searches for 40 in the list [10, 20, 30]. 40 is not present. The insertion point for 40 would be index 3. When the element is not found, binarySearch returns -(insertion point) - 1 = -(3) - 1 = -4.

The Collections.fill() method replaces all elements in the list with the specified value 5, so the list becomes [5, 5, 5].

The disjoint() method checks whether two collections have no elements in common. It returns true if they do not have common elements.

Collections.max(list) returns the maximum element according to natural ordering. Character follows Unicode (ASCII) value ordering, not alphabetical logic.
Unicode values:
'1' → 49
'a' → 97
'y' → 121
'z' → 122
Since 'z' has the highest Unicode value, it is considered the maximum.

